      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let's focus on the technical steps for profiling tools.\n\nTo systematically find the source of the memory leak, I'd recommend the following steps:\n\n1. **Use a memory profiling tool**: There are several tools available, such as Valgrind, AddressSanitizer, or Memory Profiler, that can help you identify memory leaks. These tools can analyze your code and provide information on which objects are being retained even after they're no longer needed.\n2. **Enable memory debugging**: Many compilers, including GCC and Clang, offer memory debugging options. For example, with GCC, you can use the `-fsanitize=address` flag to enable AddressSanitizer.\n3. **Run your program under the profiling tool**: Once you've set up the profiling tool, run your program under its supervision. This will allow the tool to track memory allocations and deallocations in real-time.\n4. **Analyze the profiling results**: After running your program under the profiling tool, analyze the results to identify which objects are being retained and which functions are responsible for the memory leaks.\n5. **Use a heap profiler**: A heap profiler can help you understand how memory is being allocated and deallocated in",
